#Create a function to draw a perfect standard normal distribution
plotNormal <- function(mean=0, sd=1) { 
    curve( dnorm(x,mean,sd), xlim=c(mean-4*sd,mean+4*sd) )
}

#Call this function
plotNormal()

6 Exercise 6

#Use the function to draw the normal distribution with mean 100 and standard deviation 15
plotNormal(mean=100, sd=15)

#Create an improved version of plotNormal
plotNormal <- function(mean=0, sd=1, shademin=NA, shademax=NA, twotailed=F, shadecol='red') { 
    # plots normal distribution
    curve(dnorm(x,mean,sd),xlim=c(mean-4*sd,mean+4*sd),xlab='',ylab='',xaxt='n')

    if (!(is.na(shademin) & is.na(shademax))) { # if shademin and/or shademax are set
        # draw shaded area
        if (is.na(shademin)) { shademin <- mean - 4*sd } # default shademin: left side of plot
        if (is.na(shademax)) { shademax <- mean + 4*sd } # default shademax: right side of plot
        polygon(c(shademin,seq(shademin,shademax,0.01),shademax), 
                c(0,dnorm(seq(shademin,shademax,0.01),mean,sd),0),col=shadecol, border=shadecol)
    }

    # x-axis labels and vertical lines at sd's
    axis(1, at=seq(mean-3*sd,mean+3*sd,by=sd), cex.axis=1.3, 
         labels=round(seq(mean-3*sd,mean+3*sd,by=sd),1))
    for (i in c(-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3)) { 
       segments(mean+i*sd,par("usr")[3],mean+i*sd,dnorm(mean=mean,sd=sd,mean+sd*i), 
                lty=ifelse(i==0,1,3),col='gray')
    }
}

#Use the improved function to draw the normal distribution of IQ score with the probability drawn of at least an IQ of 115

7 Exercise 7

#95% confidence interval
#1. Calculate the standard error
se <- 15/sqrt(25)

#2. This is the lower bound
105-2*se
## [1] 99
#3. This is the upper bound
105+2*se
## [1] 111

The 95% confidence interval of the sample mean means that 95% of the sample means lie within -2 up to +2 standard error of the population mean. So there is a 95% chance that the sample mean lies within the range of -2 up to +2 standard error of the population mean. How far its off the population mean depends on the standard error.

#99% confidence interval
#1. Calculate the standard error
se <- 15/sqrt(25)

#2. This is the lower bound
105-2.6*se
## [1] 97.2
#3. This is the upper bound
105+2.6*se
## [1] 112.8

8 Exercise 8

Null hypothesis: The mean IQ of people in Groningen is the same as the population mean (100) Alternative hypothesis: The mean IQ of people in Groningen is higher than the population mean (100)

We should use a one-tailed test, because we only want to assess whether if it a higher IQ than the population. This means we only want to look at one tail (the right side).

#1. Convert the sample mean to z-score (use standard error)
sigma <- 15
mu <- 100
m <- 105
n <- 25
(se <- sigma/sqrt(n))
## [1] 3
(zval <- (m - mu) /se)
## [1] 1.666667
#2. Calculate the p-value
pnorm(zval, lower.tail = FALSE)
## [1] 0.04779035
#3. Compare the p-value with the a-value

p-value is 0.04779035, whereas a-value is 0.05. The difference is significant, because the p-value is <= than the a-value. This means we do reject the null hypothesis, because there is strong evidence against the null hypothesis. This means we assume the alternative hypothesis is true.

We use standard error when converting the sample mean to z-score.

#Critical z-value
qnorm(p=0.05, mean=100, sd=se, lower.tail=F)
## [1] 104.9346

9 Exercise 9

#What was the hypotheses if question was whether or not IQ was significantly different from the population?

Null hypothesis: The mean IQ of people in Groningen is the same as the population mean (100) Alternative hypothesis: The mean IQ of people in Groningen is not equal to the population mean (100)

To test this hypothesis we would use a two-sided z-test.

#Calculate p-value for two-sided z-test with pnorm
pnorm(105, mean=100, sd=se)
## [1] 0.9522096

p-value is 0.9522096, whereas a-value is 0.025. Since it is a two-sided r-test, it should be in the lower 2,5% or the upper 2,5%. With a p-value of 95%, it is in neither of those. This means it is not significant and we do not reject the null hypothesis.

#Critical z-value for two-sided z-test
qnorm(p=0.025, mean=100, sd=se)
## [1] 94.12011
#The effect size is the difference between m (105) and u (100) divided by the standard deviation of the sample group
(105-100)/15
## [1] 0.3333333
#Visualizing the two-sided example
zvis(105, 100, 15, 25)

10 Exercise 10

#State hypotheses:

Null hypothesis: The mean Dutch proficiency test score of people living in Groningen is equal to the population mean (7) Alternative hypothesis: The mean Dutch proficiency test score of people living in Groningen is lower than the population mean (7)

To test this we use a one-tailed significance test, because we want to check the left side.

#Standard error
(se <- 2/sqrt(64))
## [1] 0.25
#z-value
(zscore <- ((6.5-7) / se))
## [1] -2
#p-value
(pval <- pnorm(zval, lower.tail = T))
## [1] 0.9522096
#critical value
qnorm(p=0.05, mean=7, sd=se)
## [1] 6.588787

Since 6.5 is lower than 6.588787, we reject our null hypothesis. The difference is significant. We accept our alternative hypothesis.

#Visualizing the lower-tail example
zvis(6.5, 7, 2, 64, "left")

#Effect size
(6.5-7)/2
## [1] -0.25

11 Exercise 11

#Standard error
(se <- 2/sqrt(64))
## [1] 0.25
#z-value
(zscore <- ((6.5-7) / se))
## [1] -2
#p-value
(pval <- pnorm(zval, lower.tail = T))
## [1] 0.9522096
#critical value
qnorm(p=0.01, mean=7, sd=se)
## [1] 6.418413

Since 6.5 is higher than 6.418413, we do not reject our null hypothesis, because it is not a significant result now.

#Visualizing the lower-tail example
zvis(6.5, 7, 2, 64, "left", alpha=0.01)

#Effect size
(6.5-7)/2
## [1] -0.25
